<subSubSection id="C33D439EFFB2FFE5FF5AFCC80369FCFD" box="[199,1028,837,862]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B981015FFB2FFE5FF5AFCC80369FCFD" blockId="17.[151,1437,402,1042]" box="[199,1028,837,862]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="B953CC07FFB2FFE5FF5AFCC80623FCFD" bold="true" box="[199,334,837,862]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name refers to the spicules on the aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33D439EFFB2FFE5FF5AFCE40786FBB2" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B981015FFB2FFE5FF5AFCE40786FBB2" blockId="17.[151,1437,402,1042]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="B953CC07FFB2FFE5FF5AFCE40659FC21" bold="true" box="[199,308,873,898]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is similar to several species, all predominantly black with the apical area of the forewing paler and with a relatively slender body (see under 
<taxonomicName id="4C276B96FFB2FFE5FCE8FC030481FC06" authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" box="[885,1004,910,933]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvata">
<emphasis id="B953CC07FFB2FFE5FCE8FC0304EEFC06" box="[885,899,910,933]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B953CC07FFB2FFE5FC0AFC030481FC06" box="[919,1004,910,933]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">curvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="4C276B96FFB2FFE5FA89FC0302F1FC05" authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" box="[1300,1436,909,934]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spiculata">
<emphasis id="B953CC07FFB2FFE5FA89FC0302F1FC05" box="[1300,1436,909,934]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. spiculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resemble those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C276B96FFB2FFE5FEF3FC3F06B5FC69" authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" box="[366,472,945,970]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tumida">
<emphasis id="B953CC07FFB2FFE5FEF3FC3F06B5FC69" box="[366,472,945,970]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. tumida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In both species the aedeagus has a well developed dorsal apodeme and the shaft curved dorsally. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C276B96FFB2FFE5FEEBFC5B0696FC4D" authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" box="[374,507,981,1006]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spiculata">
<emphasis id="B953CC07FFB2FFE5FEEBFC5B0696FC4D" box="[374,507,981,1006]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. spiculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the shaft of the aedeagus has spicules on the lateral margin that are absent in 
<taxonomicName id="4C276B96FFB2FFE5FA1AFC5B0788FBB1" authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tumida">
<emphasis id="B953CC07FFB2FFE5FA1AFC5B0788FBB1" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. tumida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
